The '''2009 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Tournament''' was held from May 9 through May 25, 2009. This was the 39th annual Division I [[NCAA Men's Lacrosse Championship]] tournament. Sixteen NCAA Division I college men's [[college lacrosse|lacrosse]] teams met after having played their way through a regular season, and for some, a conference tournament, to play in the NCAA Tournament.

The first round of the tournament was played on May 9th and 10th at the home fields of the seeded teams. The quarterfinals were held on May 16 and 17th on neutral site fields at [[Hofstra University]] ([[James M. Shuart Stadium]]) and the [[United States Naval Academy]] ([[Navy-Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]]). The tournament culminated with the semifinals and final held on [[Memorial Day]] weekend at [[Gillette Stadium]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/news/story?id=3202922&campaign=rss&source=NCAAHeadlines 2009 lacrosse finals to be played at Gillette Stadium], [[ESPN]], January 18, 2008.</ref>  The tournament was won by [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|Syracuse University]] who defeated [[Cornell University]], 10<U+2013>9, in [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] in front of 41,935 fans.<ref>[http://suathletics.com/sports/2009/5/25/MLAX_0525092654.aspx?id=6546 Syracuse 10, Cornell 9 (OT)], [[Syracuse University]], May 25, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUny8VF Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref>
{{TOClimit|3}}
==Qualifying teams==
The NCAA Division I Men<U+2019>s Lacrosse Committee selected the participating teams for the championship tournament. The committee announced the qualifying teams and the [[Single-elimination tournament#Seeding|seeding]] order on Sunday, May 3, 2009. Seven [[College lacrosse#NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse|conferences]] received automatic bids for their top team. The remaining nine teams were selected by the committee as "at-large" bids.<ref name = select>[http://www.ncaa.com/sports/m-lacros/spec-rel/050309aak.html The Roads To Foxborough Begin], [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]], May 3, 2009.</ref> 

Five conferences held tournament championships, which also determined their NCAA bids. [[Siena Saints men's lacrosse|Siena]] earned an automatic bid by winning the [[Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference]] (MAAC) championship for both their first conference title and first NCAA tournament appearance.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=189560 Siena Wins the 2009 MAAC Men<U+2019>s Lacrosse Championship], ''[[Inside Lacrosse]]'', May 3, 2009.</ref> [[Villanova Wildcats men's lacrosse|Villanova]] earned an automatic bid by winning [[Colonial Athletic Association]] (CAA) championship and also made its NCAA tournament debut.<ref name = CAA>[http://www.caasports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=43063&SPID=3811&DB_OEM_ID=8500&ATCLID=3732872 Villanova, Hofstra To Represent CAA In 2009 NCAA Men<U+2019>s Lacrosse Championships], [[Colonial Athletic Association]], May 3, 2009.</ref> [[Navy Midshipmen men's lacrosse|Navy]] earned an automatic bid by winning its fifth [[Patriot League]] championship in six years.<ref>[http://patriotleague.cstv.com/sports/m-lacros/spec-rel/042708aab.html Navy Men's Lacrosse Will Open 2009 NCAA Tournament At Third-Seeded Duke], [[Patriot League]], May 3, 2009.</ref>  Both [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Notre Dame]] and [[UMBC Retrievers men's lacrosse|UMBC]] repeated as conference champions by winning the [[Great Western Lacrosse League]] (GWLL) and [[America East Conference]], respectively.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207014 Men's Lacrosse: Notre Dame Wins GWLL Title], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 3, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.americaeast.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=59672&SPID=6539&ATCLID=3732506&DB_OEM_ID=14000 UMBC Repeats as Men's Lacrosse Champions], [[America East Conference]], May 2, 2009.</ref>

Two conferences awarded their bids based on regular season performance. [[UMass Minutemen lacrosse|UMass]] earned the [[ECAC Lacrosse League|Eastern College Athletic Conference]] (ECAC) championship and its automatic with a 6<U+2013>1 conference record.<ref>[http://www.ecacsports.com/lacrosse/2009/news/UMass_ECAC_Champs No. 15 UMass Captures ECAC Crown, NCAA Tourney Berth In 11<U+2013>10 OT Win At Rutgers], [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]], May 2, 2009.</ref> The [[Ivy League]] awarded its automatic bid to [[Cornell Big Red men's lacrosse|Cornell]]. [[Princeton Tigers|Princeton]] and Cornell possessed identical conference records and were named co-champions. The head-to-head regular season game, which Cornell had won, acted as the tie-breaking criterion.<ref name=ivy>[http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/article.asp?intID=7158 Ivy Men's Lax Earn Three NCAA Bids], [[Ivy League]], May 4, 2009.</ref> 

The remaining nine berths were awarded to at-large teams. [[Duke Blue Devils men's lacrosse|Duke]] won the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) tournament for the third straight season,<ref>[http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-lacros/recaps/042609aaa.html Duke Captures Third Straight ACC Men's Lacrosse Crown], [[Atlantic Coast Conference]], April 26, 2009.</ref> but the league does not receive an automatic bid because it does not have at least six members.<ref name = ACC>[http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-lacros/spec-rel/050409aaa.html All Four ACC Teams Earn Bids to the 2009 NCAA Men's Lacrosse Championship], Atlantic Coast Conference, May 3, 2009.</ref><ref>John Driscoll, [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=3366314&type=story Terps look to continue surprising season in ACC tournament], ESPN, April 25, 2008.</ref> Nevertheless, all four ACC teams received at-large bids: Duke, [[Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse|Maryland]], [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's lacrosse|North Carolina]], and [[Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse|Virginia]].<ref name=ACC/> Additionally, the NCAA Selection Committee awarded at-large bids to: independents [[Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse|Johns Hopkins]] and [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|Syracuse]], [[Brown Bears men's lacrosse|Brown]] and Princeton of the Ivy League, and [[Hofstra Pride|Hofstra]] of the CAA.<ref name = select/><ref name=ivy/>

