==Game summaries==
===First round===
''[[The Washington Times]]'' described the first round of the tournament as "[[wikt:chalk|chalky]]", because seven of the eight seeded teams advanced.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/09/chalky-so-far/ Chalky so far], ''[[The Washington Times]]'', May 9, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUUJaiI Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> Every past NCAA tournament had been won by seven of the eight teams that advanced to the quarterfinals, with Duke being the only one to have never won a national title.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/10/a-weekend-for-the-bluebloods/ A weekend for the bluebloods], ''The Washington Times'', May 10, 2009.</ref> For the first time, all four [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) teams advanced to the second round. It was just the second time in tournament history that four teams from the same conference advanced. The first instance occurred in [[1990 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|1990]] with Brown, [[Harvard Crimson|Harvard]], Princeton, and [[Yale Bulldogs|Yale]] of the [[Ivy League]].<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/14/acc-leads-lacrosse-conference-call/ ACC leads lacrosse conference call], ''The Washington Times'', May 14, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUcQ9ek Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref>

The tournament began on Saturday, May 9, when the [[Brown Bears|Brown Bears]] traveled to face the eighth-seeded [[Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse|Johns Hopkins Blue Jays]] at [[Homewood Field]] in [[Baltimore]]. The Blue Jays pulled away to three-goal leads in the first and final quarters, but the Bears equalized both times. In the final ten seconds of regulation, Brown [[field lacrosse#Attackmen|attackman]] Kyle Hollingsworth batted in a loose ball to even the score, 11<U+2013>11. In [[overtime (sports)|overtime]], Hopkins won the [[faceoff#Other sports|faceoff]] and called a timeout, before Brian Christopher drove up the right side of the field and made a game-winning top-corner shot on the run. It was the third overtime goal by Christopher in Hopkins' past four games.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/09/warrior-may-madness-in-game-blog-brown-at-no-2-johns-hopkins/ Warrior May Madness: In-Game Blog - Brown at No. 8 Johns Hopkins], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 9, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUVarGT Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref>

[[UMBC Retrievers|UMBC]] then played at number-six seed [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's lacrosse|North Carolina]]. The UMBC Retrievers possessed the most efficient [[field lacrosse#Penalties|extra-man offense]] (EMO) and the best-rated [[field lacrosse#Midfielders|midfield]] in the nation. Their roster, however, lacked depth, and the first-string midfielders were forced to play in the {{F to C|90}}&nbsp;heat for almost the entire game. At halftime, the Retrievers led the Tar Heels, 8<U+2013>6. The lead changed hands several times in the third period, before North Carolina took control for the remainder of the game to win, 15<U+2013>13. Tar Heels attackman Billy Bitter, who attempted only nine shots, matched the school single-game record with eight goals.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/09/warrior-may-madness-ncaa-first-round-in-game-blog-umbc-at-no-6-north-carolina/ Warrior May Madness: NCAA First Round In-Game Blog <U+2013> UMBC at No. 6 North Carolina], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 9, 2009.</ref>

[[Hofstra Pride|Hofstra]] played at fifth-seeded [[Cornell Big Red men's lacrosse|Cornell]], where the teams were even at halftime, 5<U+2013>5. The third period was the decisive quarter, and Cornell won three face-offs and outscored Hofstra five-to-one.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/09/warrior-may-madness-ncaa-first-round-in-game-blog-hofstra-at-no-5-cornell/ Warrior May Madness: NCAA First Round In-Game Final <U+2013> Cornell 11, Hofstra 8], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 9, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUXSicE Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> In [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], third-seeded [[Duke Blue Devils|Duke]] hosted [[Navy Midshipmen men's lacrosse|Navy]]. At halftime, the Blue Devils led 10<U+2013>0 and expanded the rout to 13<U+2013>1 at the start of the final period. Duke advanced with a final score of 14<U+2013>5.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/09/warrior-may-madness-ncaa-first-round-in-game-blog-navy-at-no-3-duke/ Warrior May Madness: NCAA First Round In-Game Blog: Navy at No. 3 Duke], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 9, 2009.</ref>

The second day of the tournament began with the [[Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse|Maryland Terrapins]] facing the seventh-seeded [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Notre Dame Fighting Irish]] at home in {{city-state|South Bend|Indiana}}. The Fighting Irish entered the game in possession of a perfect 15<U+2013>0 record, but still considered an unknown variable due to their schedule.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/10/maryland-moves-along/ Maryland moves along], ''The Washington Times'', May 10, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUZNutr Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> The magazine ''[[Inside Lacrosse]]'' called the Terrapins a talented team that had underachieved during the regular season.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/11/warrior-may-madness-superlatives-from-the-first-round-of-the-ncaa-lacrosse-tournament/ Warrior May Madness: Superlatives from the first round of the NCAA lacrosse tournament], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 11, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUaZhv9 Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> The first-ranked Notre Dame [[field lacrosse#Defensemen|defense]] frustrated Maryland, but the Terps still managed to gain a 6<U+2013>1 lead in the third quarter. Maryland's defense effectively shut-down Notre Dame and the leading Irish scorer Ryan Hoff was unable to make a single shot on goal.<ref>[http://blogs.insidelacrosse.com/2009/05/10/warrior-may-madness-ncaa-first-round-in-game-blog-maryland-at-no-7-notre-dame/ Warrior May Madness: NCAA First Round In-Game Blog: Maryland 7, Notre Dame 3], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 10, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207319 Maryland's defense dominates Notre Dame in 7<U+2013>3 win], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 10, 2009.</ref> Maryland was the only unseeded team to advance to the quarterfinals.<ref name=bracket/>

Both schools making their inaugural NCAA tournament appearance suffered quick elimination. The [[Villanova Wildcats men's lacrosse|Villanova Wildcats]] were trounced by the [[Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse|Virginia Cavaliers]], 18<U+2013>6. The Cavaliers were led by Brian Carroll's career-high five goal performance.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207336 Virginia routs Villanova, 18<U+2013>6], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 10, 2009.</ref> The [[Siena Saints men's lacrosse|Siena Saints]] were held scoreless for nearly 42&nbsp;minutes in their loss to the [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|Syracuse Orange]], 11<U+2013>4.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207345 Syracuse stifles Siena, 11<U+2013>4], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 11, 2009.</ref> [[Onondaga Community College]] transfer Cody Jamieson, who had just been cleared academically, scored three goals in his first start for the Orange.<ref>Conor Orr, [http://media.www.dailyorange.com/media/storage/paper522/news/2009/05/07/Sports/Off-And.Running.Syracuse.Mens.Lacrosse.Advances.To.Second.Round.Of.Ncaa.Tourname-3739590.shtml Off and running: Syracuse men's lacrosse advances to second round of NCAA tournament with win over Siena], ''[[The Daily Orange]]'', May 10, 2009.</ref> 

At [[Princeton University]], the Tigers defeated the visiting [[UMass Minutemen men's lacrosse|UMass Minutemen]], 10<U+2013>7. Princeton was led by Mark Kovler's six-point effort. The game was the final in the collegiate career of Minutemen goalkeeper [[Doc Schneider]] who led his team to the [[2006 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2006 championship game]] as a [[freshman]]. His opposite number, Princeton's Tyler Fiorito, became just the second freshman goalkeeper to start an NCAA tournament game for the Tigers.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207337 Kovler leads Princeton past Massachusetts, 10<U+2013>7], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 10, 2009.</ref>

===Quarterfinals===
[[File:UNC Lacrosse.jpg|thumb|250px|Duke and North Carolina met twice earlier in 2009, including during the ACC championship (''pictured'').]]
The quarterfinals took place over the weekend of May 16 to 17 at two neutral sites. The first doubleheader was sponsored on Saturday by [[Hofstra University]], followed by games held at the [[United States Naval Academy]] on Sunday. Despite overcast weather at both locations, it was the first time that each NCAA quarterfinals venue attracted in excess of 11,000 spectators.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/18/quarters-for-your-thoughts/ Quarters for your thoughts], ''The Washington Times'', May 18, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUf1vCR Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref>

The second round opened at Hofstra's [[James M. Shuart Stadium]] with the Maryland<U+2013>Syracuse match-up. Al Cavalieri filled in as the Orange goalkeeper for long-time starter John Galloway who was sick with the flu. Syracuse scored three unanswered goals in the first quarter before Maryland goalie Brian Phipps suffered an [[anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] tear. Terrapins midfielder Grant Catalino narrowed the deficit to 5<U+2013>3 before halftime on an extra-man score. In the second half, Syracuse made defensive adjustments to shut-down Maryland's behind-the-goal attack,<ref>[http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/lacrosse/blog/2009/05/postscript_from_maryland_vs_sy.html Postscript from Maryland vs. Syracuse], ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', May 17, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUgOWxQ Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> and the Orange tallied three times in the span of 2:10 to pull away in the third quarter. Syracuse won, 11<U+2013>6, and extended its postseason streak against Maryland to five.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207463 Syracuse Advances to Semifinals With 11<U+2013>6 Victory Over Maryland], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 16, 2009.</ref>

Ivy League rivals Cornell and Princeton then had their 70th meeting, but first in the NCAA tournament.<ref><!--[http://www.theithacajournal.com/article/20090516/SPORTS03/905160373/1128/New+wrinkle+to+Cornell-Princeton+lacrosse+rivalry --> "New wrinkle in the Cornell Princeton lacrosse rivalry", ''[[The Ithaca Journal]]'', May 16, 2009.</ref> Earlier in the postseason, the Big Red defeated the Tigers to split the Ivy League championship.<ref>[http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/college/lacrosse/bal-sp.laxrup17may17,0,453351.story Cornell men defeat Princeton, head to NCAA final four], ''The Baltimore Sun'', May 17, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUi4NTg Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> Three Princeton shots hit the post in the first half of the second quarter, and Cornell entered halftime with a 5<U+2013>1 advantage. In the third quarter, Tigers attackman Tommy Davis ended their 27:58 scoring drought with a 15-yard shot. Princeton quickly tallied again with 28 seconds in the period. In the final quarter, the Big Red withstood two penalties to win, 6<U+2013>4.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207464 Cornell Wins Defensive Struggle Against Princeton, Advances to Final Four], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 16, 2009.</ref>

The second day of the quarterfinals took place at [[Navy-Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland]]. The first game featured top-ranked Virginia and Johns Hopkins.<ref name=uvajhu/> The Cavaliers dominated the Blue Jays, 19<U+2013>8, in their worst postseason defeat in school history.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/weblogs/d1scourse/2009/may/17/final-virginia-19-hopkins-8/ Final: Virginia 19, Hopkins 8], ''The Washington Times'', May 17, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUkm3Kg Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> Shamel Bratton of Virginia scored a career-high five goals. The victory marked the 300th of head coach [[Dom Starsia]]'s career, and he became the third coach in [[Division I]] lacrosse history to win as many games. Virginia advanced to their fourth Final Four appearance in five seasons.<ref name=uvajhu>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207490 Virginia beats Johns Hopkins 19<U+2013>8 in NCAA Quarterfinals], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 17, 2009.</ref> With the quarterfinals elimination of both Maryland and Johns Hopkins, 2009 became only the third time since [[1971 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|the NCAA tournament began]] that no team from [[Maryland|the state]] participated in the Final Four.<ref>[http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/lacrosse/blog/2009/05/where_art_thou_maryland.html Where art thou, Maryland?], ''The Baltimore Sun'', May 18, 2009.</ref>

The final game of the round featured [[Carolina-Duke rivalry|intrastate rivals]] Duke and North Carolina in their third meeting of the season.<ref>[http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20090515/ARTICLES/905159934/1005?Title=ACC-Insider-Duke-UNC-rivalry-hardly-lax-during-basketball-offseason ACC Insider: Duke-UNC rivalry hardly lax during basketball offseason], ''[[The Wilmington Star-News]]'', May 15, 2009.</ref> In the first quarter, the Blue Devils jumped out to an early lead and survived a two-man-down penalty, but the Tar Heels scored four unanswered goals to briefly take the lead in the second quarter. Late in the final period, North Carolina rallied from a four-point deficit to trail by one goal, 12<U+2013>11. As time expired, a shot by Sean Delaney missed high over the goal, and Duke defeated North Carolina for the third time of the year. The Blue Devils' Zach Howell scored a career-high three goals and [[Tewaaraton Trophy]] finalist Ned Crotty tallied twice and had six assists.<ref name=dukeunc>[http://www.newsobserver.com/sports/college/duke/story/1531735.html Duke lacrosse ousts UNC], ''[[The News & Observer]]'', May 18, 2009. Accessed 2009-06-07.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5iiUlo5eb Archived] 2009-08-01.</ref> The Duke defense held Carolina's leading scorer, Billy Bitter, to just two assists.<ref>[http://insidelacrosse.com/page.cfm?pagerid=2&news=fdetail&storyid=207492 Duke edges North Carolina to return to Final Four], ''Inside Lacrosse'', May 17, 2009.</ref>

